Part 2: Htf does somebody hack into a voting booth (or anything for that matter)?
  So how does someone "hack" into a voting booth? A better question, how does someone hack into any computer or software system? There are generally two ways: 1) steal or guess a user's username and password which grants access to the importer, or 2) exploit a security flaw in the software that just allows access. #2 is a bit easier to understand, there are all sorts of examples of this (SITE). All those big stories you see usually involve security issues. One of the craziest I saw was someone hitting the delete button 14 times on a Linux machine which then gave them sudo access https://www.lifehacker.com.au/2015/12/you-can-break-into-a-linux-system-by-pressing-backspace-28-times-heres-how-to-fix-it/. How the hell did they figure that out? I just imagine a room full of monkeys banging on keyboards until they get into the system...or Hamlet is written. (Potential business idea: create computer security company which hires people to press buttons on computers all day in the hopes they will discover security flaws)

  Let's talk about #1: getting a user's credentials and just accessing the system as if you were them. This sounds like something from Misison Impossible, yet it happens all the time. This usually involves some kind of social engineering - someone being tricked into giving up their credentials. Like getting a call from a bank claiming there is an issue with your account and they need your name/SSN/address/account numbers. Don't give them that info! If it's the bank then call them back.

Or someone can simply guess your password, or even pretend to be you to gain access. Sarah Palin had her Yahoo! account https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sarah_Palin_email_hack hacked years ago because someone reset her password. You read that right. They got her email address, tried to login, hit the "I forgot my password" button, and then successfully answered her security questions...the answers to which they guessed just from listening to her speeches. For example: "where did you meet your husband?" "In college." Yeah right...they met on Alaskan's Only (SITE: find Alaskan dating website)

  Another common way hackers gain access are by "phishing attacks." You've probably seen this term come up before...and possibly been confused by it like I usually am, cause the name doesn't make much sense. A phishing attack usually involves spam email, like one that says "send me your password" or "You need to click THIS LINK to update your password." Everyone at a company, like one of the ones who make voting booth software, all get a spam email saying they need to reset their Gmail passwords. But its not from Gmail, its from a hacker. Sometimes these are easy to spot, and you've probably received emails from people like "ALLCAPSNAME@zimbabe.com". Yet these can oftentimes be much more sophisticated. Now you know why your company makes you take those corporate compliant tests which teach you NOT to respond to emails which sound a bit shady.

  The really sophisticated ones involve using multiple types of social engineering and trying to get up to a big prize. Suppose everyone at a voting software company received an email like what's described above. While it's a long shot, all they would need is a single person to fall into their trap and give up their credentials. And then...the hackers do nothing. The person continues logging in with their new password, and doesn't even realize they
  ve been hacked. But then months later they could send *another* coworker an email from the now-hacked email, asking them to open a program in Microsoft Word...but actually this releases opens a program that infects the new user's computer with a virus and maybe gets deeper into their security. Then come voting day they have access to the company's system and can hopefully change votes. This sounds far-fetched but in fact <a href="https://www.miaminewtimes.com/news/russian-hackers-broke-into-vr-systems-elections-company-used-by-miami-broward-9397965">this is exactly what happened in 2016</a> during the presidential election.

One of the problems is there should be way more failsafes in place than just usernames or passwords. So take a lesson from Sarah Palin...come up with harder (or fake) answers to security questions, and strong passwords. Use LastPass or something similar. It's been said multiple times, but seriously, DON'T OPEN LINKS sent in email unless you know or trust who the message is from. Also, while we're on the topic, don't think that fingerprints or facial recognition is any more secure...a digital photo or ink on some tape is good enough to get past these systems. What ever happened to two-factor authentication?!? Let's look at some ways to make these voting systems more secure.

