  Part 3: Making voting booths unhackable.
So what can be done? First off let's take the social-engineering aspect from before and apply them to the people actually working at voting stations on election day. While I appreciate the old ladies volunteering their time at my local school on election day, the two of them alone are not enough. We probably need more alert volunteers, and some tech-saavy folks working at the voting booths. Some shady stuff can go down at voting booths with a bunch of people in line and all the mayhem (SITE/PIC).

There are only (SITE) XX number of companies who make the software for voting booths. I don't like the federal govt being in charge of too much (or really anything besides education standards and regulations), and similarly I don't think a one-size-fits-all model is a good idea for the software running on voting systems. It's a honeypot for hackers. Instead let's have 50 different companies each in charge of the security in each state. That way instead of hacking into one system/company, you have to hack 50. Also, different states have different kinds of elections, hold them at different times, etc. More power to the states! For instance, in Iowa they do caucuses, but in Michigan they do primaries. Sticky. Plus it allows the feds to shell out money for others to work...more jobs! Having lots of different companies which are overseen by a federal committee helps get around most of the social engineering stuff,, so how do we make the software running on the booths more secure in the first place?

Also online voting. It seems that the mainstream politicians don't want to talk about this...even though Democrats are for the people and their rights to vote. Give me a break. The only ones I heard talking about online voting and/or online registration was Jill Stein and Bernie Sanders...SITE? But unfortunately the age-old adage by politicians is that its not "secure." I invite you to read the first part of this blog...our current system is not secure. And in fact they are wrong. We all bank online, why can't we vote online?

   TALK ABOUT THE SECURITY OF THAT!!!

  The major concern with online voting is to ensure somebody is who they claim to be. There are all sorts of ways to do this. SSN numbers; IP address checking to make sure the person who is voting for a candidate in State A is in State A. When we register to vote we are usually mailed a card with a certain identifier on it; that used in conjunction with a person's SSN, burthdate, driver's license, or other form of ID should be enough to verify a person's identity. Voters could be given a window in which to verify they can log into the system.

  Here's how I see it going down. One month before the elections in a certain state, all registered voters are sent mail saying if they want to vote online they can, and here is a unique key for each voter plus a url. The user navigates to the page, and the page checks their IP or location, verifying they are in fact in the town or county. So you can't vote online if you're out of state...you still have to go through the old absentee voter way. Once they are verified to be in a good location, they enter the key and a page comes up showing their name and address. "Is this correct?" the system asks. After that, the user can choose a form of PID to prove they are themselves: entering their SSN, Driver's License Number, etc. After this is verified, the usre can choose a PIN to login within 24 hours of election day to vote. Once again when logging in on election day, they will only need to provide their PIN and email. Notice that for someone to hack or fake a person's credentials, you would have to a) intercept their snail mail, b) access 

   If not, there is then the absentee approach. Then once someone votes they're locked out...someone can then log a complaint if they cant get into the system. There are definitely kinks to work out so we should start this on a small scale in local or state elections and then build up to federal ones. Going along with what I mentioned above, f there was more voting online then the federal overnment could contract different companies in each state to design secure websites and apps...again now there are over 50 systems to hack into as opposed to just one or two.

   This involves better crypto on the machines themselves (ie. more jobs for crypto geeks), and better workers monitoring booths (more jobs). 
   Also it means better security audits on the companies that make the voting machines in the first place...more jobs!

Blockchain technology can also be used SITE...I don't want to get into this right now but suffice it to say that the same underlying tech used for Bitcoin and other crypto-currencies can also be used to ensure fair voting systems.

We've now spent billions of dollars on better voting software, educating voters, and getting more workers at the poll. Unfortunately all this does is get us back to square one: we have now ensured that only the people who voted get their votes counted and they were not changed. But this does nothing to actually fix our voting system!. Read on (the next section is neither about tech nor the Rust Belt, its just my opinions and facts about voting, so feel free to skip).
  


