  The Beauty of the Rust Belt
  Recently I was in Lake Erie wine country in New York and Pennsylvania. Now the wine there is not as good as what you would find in California or Oregon for instance, as the climate can't support what theirs can. But having been to Napa, Sonoma, and different vineyards around Portland, I can say that the vineyards up around Lake Erie are just as beautiful as their west coast counterparts.

How could they not be? You have beautiful grape trees (bushes? vines? I don't really know how those things grow) plus cherry and apple trees, with the Appalachian Mountains on one side, and Lake Erie on the other. I think that most people who have not been to the Great Lakes assume they are nothing special, just really big lakes, since the name kind of implies that and looking at them on a map they don't seem like much. In actuality they are HUGE, and when you see them the word "ocean" seems more appropriate. Standing on the banks of any of them is more reminiscent of standing on the Mediterranean or Gulf of Mexico. I will write a much longer post about the Great Lakes in the future.

Oh and to top it all off, its Fall and the leaves are changing and had some nice color in them! Where would you rather be on a fall afternoon than this picturesque location in the Rust Belt? Other than watching football, obvi. Plus 

  I bring this all up because
  a) I need to get in a quick post cause my ass has been slacking
  b) I am back to the real world and sad about how much I am missing wine country
  c) to talk about how beautiful the Rust Belt is.

People who haven't been here don't know what they're missing. The Great Lakes. The Appalachian Mountains. Huge forests, fields of green, wildflowers, rivers (the Ohio, Mississippi, and countless others). The climate is great - in the summer where I live it usually stays just below 90, and in the winter it can hover between the high teens and low 30s.

I love the beauty of this region. Which is why its sad that people pollute it. Wait what RBD, you're going all environmental on me?!?! Yes I am. While I am all for jobs and workers keeping their jobs to support their familes, I don't want to sacrifice this beautiful land to do so. While things like fracking, coal mining, steel mills and coke plants, oil pipelines, etc. make folks big bucks and keep the roofs over people's heads (including members of my own family), they are also destroying the land we live on, the air we breathe, and the water we drink. Counties around Pittsburgh and in WV have some of the worst air quality in the nation...mostly due to fracking. We're building pipelines over the Ohio River, putting not only the Rust Belt but practically half the country and more at risk if a spill takes place. This is ludicrous and dirty.

Plus, whether you're a republican or democrat or green or libertarian or tori or anything else, whether you work in natural gas or solar, moving to 100% renewable energy should be everyone's goal. Using fossil fuels like coal, oil, or natural gas may make sense now, but it's ultimately a dead end, since there is a limited supply of it. The Marcellus Shale may contain a billion cajillion cubic tons of natural gas, but when we run out of that stuff then we're back at square one.

So we need an exit strategy, one which preserves the beauty of the Rust Belt and world-over, and which also preserves the jobs we need to survive. Here's my idea.
    
---------------------------
New jobs from new technologies
Solar, wind, geothermal, nuclear...these are all much better energy options for the future. Unfortunately, despite what many seem to think, they can't happen overnight. It will take decades to get to a point where we can have reliable energy production to stop fossil fuel our dependence, but the work must start now. I view the youngest generation in the work force today, folks from about 22 to 40 (millenials? generation Z? who cares) as the transitional generation. It is our responsibility to transition to a world where all energy comes from renewable sources.

In the short term continue we should continue with fossil fuels (which currently make up about ___ of our energy production), but plan on phasing them out entirely within next 10 years. We need to regulate the shit out of companies too to keep them as clean as possible (this is a contested issue and I will blog about this later, but in short our regulations are failing and these companies are making the world way unsafe). We notify coal and natural gas workers that your jobs are going to disappear in 10 years...so you've got 10 years to find a new career. Workers over 45 are fine - their jobs are guaranteed for the remaining 10 years and at the end of it they get a nice retirement...the money coming from taxing the shit out of consumers of gas and coal. 44 or younger? Read on!

During those 10 years we start heavily ramping up solar, wind, geothermal, and other alternative fuel sources. TODO: link to best renewable technologies. We create programs for fossil fuel workers below 45 to get trained in these new technologies - installing/creating/fixing solar panels/windmills/geothermal units. There are ___ homes in the US and ___ commercial buildings - getting them all onto renewable energy will take a massive effort, which means lots of jobs!

Some quick numbers. We have ___ homes in the US, of which about 25% of them can sustain solar. Another ___ which can handle geothermal. TODO: look up how many jobs can be created from fossil fuels.

Unfortunately it will take a while to ramp this up, probably something like 50 years until we have enough renewable energy, so in the mid term the best solution in my opinion is nuclear. I have a lot of mixed opinions about nuclear and don't think its great in the long-term, but it is the perfect transition technology. We already have ___ nuclear plants in the US, and plans to build ____ more. Nuclear plants also employ about __ people! It takes about ___ to build a new nuclear plant, so doubling or tripling the amount we have in the next 10 years means we can almost completely replace fossil fuels with nuclear. 

How can you help with the effort? First, support regulations on fossil fuels companies. Write to your local politicians and tell them you want better air and water quality. Do some internet searches for the biggest polluters around you. Here I've already done it:
  "biggest polluters in the Rust Belt" (or substitute your state/county/city)
  "air quality in ___"
  "water quality in ___"

  The biggest violators of clean air and water are corporations, and our governmental bodies which are in bed with them and allow them to operate as they do. No matter how much we change, letting corporations continue as they are will only make things worse.

  Next, start looking into solar panels, taking public transit, or riding your bike.

