Regulations vs Tax Breaks:
As a mostly libertarian minded person, saying I am in favor of environmental regulations seems a little dirty. But in fact I am. While I think the free market is a good answer to a lot of problems, I don't see how it can stop corporations from polluting.

  In fact, I would argue that from a philosophical perspective, regulations are pretty libertarian leaning. The age old adage "you should be able to do whatever you want as long as it doesn't harm others" which libertarians preach contradicts a corporation's pollution...cause that *is* harming others. When Lake Erie catches on fire because ___, drinking water is undrinkable because of gas pipelines, and air quality is low because of coke plants or slag heaps, these corporations are profiting by poisoning others. FRACKING!!!

This is not a tongue in cheek comment: profits = revenue - costs, so by dumping waste in a river or not correctly sealing pipes to prevent gas leaks, they are in fact cutting costs, and hence raising their profits.

If you talk to someone who defends corporations like these, they usually completely ignore my point and instead argue about jobs. Ok, let's talk about jobs. I am not advocating for laying off factory workers; rather, I am advocating for corporations paying a bit extra to pass inspections. And in many cases, some of the biggest polluters don't even employ that many people. TODO: more on this...

Let's go back to regulations. People hear "regulations" and think "higher taxes." But let's go back to tax breaks. The auto, gas, and coal industries are hugely subsidized. In WI, the tax breaks recently promised to Viacom are ___, the highest ever given. And what are they doing? Pumping water out of the Great Lakes watershed - something which is very very bad. And how many jobs will it create? ____ What about fracking, natural gas, or coal? ____

Tech companies aren't exempt from this either. Just a quick side note, since Amazon is looking at multiple locations in the Rust Belt, cities are basically prostituing themselves out with tax money for HQ2. I think this is a terrible idea - you are paying a premium in taxes to *hopefully* get more jobs in an area. But there are plenty of jobs! President Trump talks about how low unemployment is; there is a shortage of workers all over. We don't need to cripple state or city budgets by cutting taxes for corporations - this is a bailout at best. And its the opposite of spending conservatively. 
  
I am all for cutting government spending, but when the government cuts its own revenue stream off, this is just stupid. Giving a FOREIGN company __ billion dollars in tax cuts makes no sense. Compared to the number of permanent jobs that will be there, it doesn't make sense.

Anectodal evidence is the worst, but I have personal experience with this so I am gonna tell my story anyway. I have family who lives in fracking country. A new steel mill was built to be used in fracking drilling. While it was being constructed the town was booming - lots of jobs for people there, engineers and scientists from all over the US were living there to help plan and build, and the local economy was doing awesome. And then a few years later once the construction ended and the real work began...the town is dead. You drive through it now and you see boarded up gas stations and grocery stores - the only places in town are a few bars, restaurants, and Dollar General. TODO: how many people are employed there? Another poster city of the Rust Belt.

So why do we scoff at regulations (TODO: do we? this might be incorrect) and welcome tax breaks for corporations that over-promise on everything and under-perform on jobs?
